# Authors and Contributors

This package is a maintained fork of the original MONECA (Mobility Network Clustering Analysis) package. We acknowledge and credit all contributors to the original work and ongoing development.

## Current Maintainer

**Giampaolo Montaletti** <giampaolo.montaletti@gmail.com>
- ORCID: https://orcid.org/0009-0002-5327-1122
- GitHub: https://github.com/gmontaletti
- Role: Current maintainer, package modernization, new features, testing suite
- Contributions: ggraph visualizations, synthetic data generation, comprehensive testing, igraph compatibility layer, documentation updates, performance optimizations

## Original Authors

**Jonas Touboel** <jt@soc.ku.dk>
- Role: Original algorithm design and methodology
- Affiliation: University of Copenhagen, Department of Sociology
- Contributions: Core MONECA algorithm, theoretical foundation, initial implementation

**Anton Grau Larsen** <agl.ioa@cbs.dk>
- Role: Original package development and implementation
- Affiliation: Copenhagen Business School
- Contributions: R package structure, initial codebase, original documentation

## About this Fork

This fork (renamed to `moneca`) continues the development and maintenance of the original MONECA package with:

- Modern visualization capabilities using ggraph
- Comprehensive testing suite with testthat
- Enhanced documentation and vignettes
- Synthetic data generation functions
- Improved error handling and input validation
- igraph compatibility layer for version 1.3.0+
- Performance optimizations and code modernization
- Active maintenance and bug fixes

## Citation

If you use this package in your research, please cite both the original methodology and the current implementation:

### Software Citation:
```
Montaletti, G., Touboel, J., & Larsen, A. G. (2024). moneca: Mobility Network 
Clustering Analysis. R package version 0.4.0. https://github.com/gmontaletti/moneca
```

### Methodological Citation:
```
Touboel, J., & Larsen, A. G. (2017). Mapping the Social Class Structure: 
From Occupational Mobility to Social Class Categories Using Network Analysis. 
Sociology, 51(6), 1257-1276. doi:10.1177/0038038516673125
```

## Acknowledgments

We thank the original authors for creating this innovative approach to social mobility analysis and making their work available to the research community. This fork aims to preserve and extend their valuable contribution while ensuring continued accessibility and development.

## Contributing

We welcome contributions from the community. Please:

1. Fork the repository
2. Create a feature branch
3. Make your changes with appropriate tests
4. Update documentation as needed
5. Submit a pull request

